TY  - JOUR
AU  - Barsky, Robert B.
AU  - De Long, J. Bradford
T1  - Why Does the Stock Market Fluctuate?*
PY  - 1993
Y1  - 1993/05/01
DO  - 10.2307/2118333
JO  - The Quarterly Journal of Economics
JA  - Q J Econ
VL  - 108
IS  - 2
SP  - 291
EP  - 311
SN  - 0033-5533
AB  - Major long-run swings in the U. S. stock market over the past century are broadly consistent with a model driven by changes in current and expected future dividends in which investors must estimate the time-varying long-run dividend growth rate. Such an estimated long-run growth rate resembles a long distributed lag on past dividend growth, and is highly correlated with the level of dividends. Prices therefore respond more than proportionately to long-run movements in dividends. The time-varying component of dividend growth need not be detectable in the dividend data for it to have large effects on stock prices.
Y2  - 3/25/2024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.2307/2118333
ER  - 



